<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-17T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-17T09:00:00-05:00" n="746" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d746">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">864.918/7–1745: Telegram</note>
                                <head>No. 746<lb/><hi rend="italic">The Representative in
                                        Hungary</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SHFA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                            State</gloss></hi><note n="1" xml:id="d746fn1">The gist
                                        of this message was included in telegram No. 65 of July 19
                                        from <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">Grew</persName> to
                                            <persName corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName> (file No.
                                        800.00 Summaries/7–1945).</note></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi></seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Budapest</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-17T16:00:00+02:00">July 17, 1945—4 p.m.</date></dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>297. <persName corresp="#p_G13">Gregoriev</persName>[,] <persName corresp="#p_PGM1">Pushkin</persName>’s Assistant[,] has
                                    asked <persName corresp="#p_BRI1">Balogh</persName> for list
                                    Hungarian newspapermen previously correspondents wholly or in
                                        <pb facs="0839" n="645" xml:id="pg_645"/> part for foreign
                                    newspapers and who will presumably engage in reporting
                                    subsequent to reestablishment international communications. This
                                    is first evidence Russians will raise blackout on foreign
                                    correspondents but there are no indications they will permit
                                    uncontrolled reporting.</p>
                                <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_SHFA1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>